19/05/2006
THE HAGUE, Netherlands -- Former Serbian President Milan Milutinovic, indicted in connection with the Kosovo conflict, will go on trial in The Hague on 10 July, the UN tribunal announced on Thursday (18 May). Also due to appear before the court as co-defendants are former Yugoslav Deputy Prime Minister Nikola Sainovic, former Defence Minister Dragoljub Ojdanic, senior army commander Vladimir Lazarevic, former General Staff chief Nebojsa Pavkovic, and the former head of the Security Service, Sreten Lukic. Most of the indictees were released, pending trial. A sixth defendant, former chief of public security Vlastimir Djordjevic, remains at large. 
In other news Thursday, the Serbian Supreme Court upheld on appeal the sentences of four members of the "Avengers" paramilitary formation, convicted of 1992 war crimes in Sjeverin. Dragutin Dragicevic and Milan Lukic, recently extradited to The Hague from Argentina, were sentenced to 20 years in prison, as was Oliver Krsmanovic, who remains a fugitive. Djordje Sevic received 15 years. The four men were responsible for torture and murder of 16 people in Sjeverin. (Reuters, B92, Beta - 18/05/06) 
